      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mixing OS X and Microsoft</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Nielsen letter comments on Sept 14 article on new Apple operating system</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The new Mac operating system, Mac OS X, sounds impressive indeed (''Apple Breaks the Mold,'' Sept. 14).</p>
        <p>If Apple really wants to set the world on fire, it should produce a version of OS X that operates on Intel Pentium machines.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The new Mac operating system, Mac OS X, sounds impressive indeed (''Apple Breaks the Mold,'' Sept. 14).</p>
        <p>If Apple really wants to set the world on fire, it should produce a version of OS X that operates on Intel Pentium machines.</p>
        <p>Microsoft would probably welcome the move, as it would provide a genuine alternative to Windows and perhaps reduce some of the legal pressures on that company.</p>
        <p>As long as Apple insists on making people buy its proprietary hardware to get its operating system, it will remain a niche player.</p>
        <p>ROBERT NIELSEN  Seattle</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
